1
00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:23,960
SPK_1: Well, hello, dear audience of my channel. Today I have a privilege of presenting you a very special guest. His name is Jordan Hall. And of all of the guests who were at my channel, he might be the one most difficult to be put in the box.

2
00:00:23,960 --> 00:00:37,380
SPK_1: That's why I would rather ask you, Jordan, to present yourself to my audience who doesn't know you yet, but I'm absolutely confident will be excited to learn about.

3
00:00:38,080 --> 00:00:52,260
SPK_0: Great. Maybe three aspects. So a big portion of my life, in the earlier period of my life in particular, was as a technology entrepreneur in the classic Silicon Valley mold.

4
00:00:52,260 --> 00:01:05,540
SPK_0: So I built a series of tech companies in the beginning of the Internet age, took them public and retired from that in 2007 when I was 36 years old, I guess.

5
00:01:06,940 --> 00:01:11,900
SPK_0: I have continued to participate in that world, but more as an investor, a board member, as an advisor.

6
00:01:11,980 --> 00:01:17,840
SPK_0: But I have some cycles where I'll pulse into it meaningfully and then pulse away.

7
00:01:18,800 --> 00:01:21,620
SPK_0: Then the second chunk, which was me.

8
00:01:22,260 --> 00:01:39,240
SPK_0: Maybe 2009 to 2022 was a world of being a highly undisciplined, largely self-taught polymath with an orientation towards the big questions.

9
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:51,760
SPK_0: In fact, that we'll talk about today, things like the metacrisis, the nature of civilization, the relationship between technology and culture and things like that, where I met a large number of really interesting people.

10
00:01:52,260 --> 00:01:54,180
SPK_0: And learned a lot of interesting things.

11
00:01:54,960 --> 00:02:14,260
SPK_0: And then the third aspect, which is the most recent, is that I was baptized and become a, I would hope to say, at least deeply committed and meaningfully disciplined, though not well disciplined, Christian in October of, not this most recent October, but the year before that.

12
00:02:14,380 --> 00:02:15,460
SPK_0: So quite brief.

13
00:02:15,760 --> 00:02:19,100
SPK_0: And this has been a significant piece, as you might imagine.

14
00:02:21,400 --> 00:02:21,960
SPK_0: Largely.

15
00:02:22,260 --> 00:02:24,200
SPK_0: Consuming piece of my life for that period of time.

16
00:02:27,020 --> 00:02:28,720
SPK_1: Could not have done it better for sure.

17
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:35,460
SPK_1: I guess, yeah, let's just jump into this big topics you already brought it up.

18
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:40,640
SPK_1: I personally find your idea of metacrisis.

19
00:02:42,820 --> 00:02:54,480
SPK_1: Maybe being one of the most eloquent, eloquent ways of describing just the current state of not just the Western civilization, but I would say the capital C.

20
00:02:56,120 --> 00:03:00,520
SPK_1: And could you help me and my audience understand them better?

21
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:02,220
SPK_1: So what is metacrisis?

22
00:03:02,240 --> 00:03:06,020
SPK_1: How it's different from all of the other things we've experienced before?

23
00:03:06,260 --> 00:03:07,660
SPK_1: And maybe why now?

24
00:03:08,460 --> 00:03:08,900
SPK_0: Okay.

25
00:03:10,460 --> 00:03:11,660
SPK_0: So I'll start.

26
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:12,660
SPK_0: I'll kind of walk up slowly.

27
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:16,800
SPK_0: The first thing is just to maybe just to notice the idea of what is a crisis.

28
00:03:17,160 --> 00:03:22,900
SPK_0: And this is from the Greek sense of something that cannot continue as what it is.

29
00:03:23,140 --> 00:03:24,080
SPK_0: So there is some.

30
00:03:24,140 --> 00:03:24,640
SPK_0: You know, it's a crisis.

31
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:36,200
SPK_0: It's usually a process or a state of affairs where there's something about the nature of that state of affairs and the nature of the context of what's happening, where a qualitative change is going to occur.

32
00:03:37,620 --> 00:03:39,040
SPK_0: Pregnancy is a crisis.

33
00:03:39,260 --> 00:03:41,500
SPK_0: There's a period where birth will happen.

34
00:03:41,580 --> 00:03:45,000
SPK_0: And that is a transition where the woman is no longer carrying the baby inside.

35
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:47,000
SPK_0: She is now nursing the baby outside.

36
00:03:47,160 --> 00:03:47,760
SPK_0: So crisis.

37
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:54,620
SPK_0: And then what we've noticed in the world now is that there are crises happening.

38
00:03:54,640 --> 00:03:55,420
SPK_0: They're happening all over the place.

39
00:03:56,060 --> 00:04:01,300
SPK_0: And some have come to call this the poly crisis or the multiplicity of crises.

40
00:04:01,900 --> 00:04:05,340
SPK_0: And you can look sort of under any rock you'd like to.

41
00:04:05,420 --> 00:04:07,020
SPK_0: There's crises in finance and economics.

42
00:04:07,120 --> 00:04:10,140
SPK_0: There's crises in birth rates.

43
00:04:10,300 --> 00:04:13,140
SPK_0: There's meaning crises and psychological crises.

44
00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:14,280
SPK_0: There's political crises.

45
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:16,040
SPK_0: There's ecological crises.

46
00:04:16,220 --> 00:04:17,740
SPK_0: There's all sorts all over the place.

47
00:04:17,780 --> 00:04:20,860
SPK_0: And some of these are, in fact, overblown.

48
00:04:20,940 --> 00:04:23,480
SPK_0: But many of them are underreported.

49
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:24,620
SPK_0: And they are all over the place.

50
00:04:24,640 --> 00:04:25,140
SPK_0: They're all happening.

51
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:27,080
SPK_0: And in some sense are continuing to proceed.

52
00:04:27,680 --> 00:04:33,120
SPK_0: Now, the next move you can make is noticing that these crises are almost never independent.

53
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:44,280
SPK_0: So, for example, we witnessed that the real estate crisis in the United States in 2007 spilled over into a series of financial crises around the world.

54
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:53,520
SPK_0: But those also spilled over into political crises or spilled over into even coordination crises that caused the COVID viral crisis to become worse.

55
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:58,540
SPK_0: Because the political crisis that had preceded it reduced our ability to respond to our environment.

56
00:04:58,640 --> 00:05:00,360
SPK_0: So you now have one level up.

57
00:05:00,420 --> 00:05:14,860
SPK_0: And then one level above that is where we begin to talk about the metacrisis, which is to say, are there deep things, things that are closer to the root that are themselves the profound foundations that are shaking?

58
00:05:15,020 --> 00:05:23,500
SPK_0: So to use the visual metaphor, if we're all sort of standing on a platform and we notice that everything on the platform is shaking, we might say, hey, everything is shaking.

59
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:24,520
SPK_0: Everything on the platform is shaking.

60
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:26,040
SPK_0: All of these things are under crisis.

61
00:05:26,440 --> 00:05:31,700
SPK_0: Or we might wonder, wait a minute, are we standing on a platform that's on a pillar and the pillar is what's shaking?

62
00:05:31,820 --> 00:05:33,280
SPK_0: In which case we need to be looking down.

63
00:05:33,760 --> 00:05:39,780
SPK_0: And that was the work that I and a number of people underwent from about, again, 2010 to 2017.

64
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:53,440
SPK_0: And the answer, as it turns out, was something like, yes, there's a relatively compact set, not one single point, but relatively compact set of deep events that are occurring.

65
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:56,380
SPK_0: Now, many of which are actually predictable.

66
00:05:56,520 --> 00:06:02,980
SPK_0: Like you could say, given a proper theory or set of theories about the nature of, say, civilization, what might we expect to occur?

67
00:06:03,660 --> 00:06:09,460
SPK_0: And that these are producing the poly crisis events that we're seeing.

68
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:20,280
SPK_0: And one of the consequences of that, as you might imagine, is that if you try to address the set of problems at the poly crisis level, at best, you're playing whack-a-mole.

69
00:06:20,340 --> 00:06:22,820
SPK_0: And in point of fact, you're usually making things worse.

70
00:06:22,820 --> 00:06:30,180
SPK_0: Because a solution that will be affecting a subset generally produces spillover effects into areas that you're not paying attention to.

71
00:06:31,340 --> 00:06:36,600
SPK_0: So can you, if you want to grasp this at all, you have to find some way of grasping it at the most foundational level.

72
00:06:36,720 --> 00:06:38,060
SPK_0: So metacrisis.

73
00:06:39,340 --> 00:06:39,880
SPK_0: How's that?

74
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:41,560
SPK_1: That sounds great.

75
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:45,660
SPK_1: And it brings me one question and one comment.

76
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:49,020
SPK_1: I will start with a short comment concerning the idea of crisis.

77
00:06:49,980 --> 00:06:52,460
SPK_1: The idea of crisis is something which cannot continue.

78
00:06:52,820 --> 00:06:59,340
SPK_1: But also, I think there is an important element of revelation in any crisis.

79
00:06:59,640 --> 00:07:03,580
SPK_1: Crisis as a process always reveals something.

80
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:08,120
SPK_1: And in that sense, I just think it kind of strengthens your arguments.

81
00:07:08,220 --> 00:07:13,520
SPK_1: We are in a process when many things which we took for granted are not for granted anymore.

82
00:07:13,780 --> 00:07:18,080
SPK_1: It reveals maybe that we are not what we think we are.

83
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:22,660
SPK_1: Or like we don't function based on the principles we say we are functioning.

84
00:07:22,820 --> 00:07:34,500
SPK_1: And this kind of constructive, revelatory element of pain or suffering or destruction, which is usually associated with crisis, I also think is happening right here, right now.

85
00:07:34,620 --> 00:07:40,460
SPK_1: In a way, it reminds of this Deuteronomy, like when it says that crisis effectively...

86
00:07:40,460 --> 00:07:42,400
SPK_1: You can say that crisis is a moment of choice.

87
00:07:42,560 --> 00:07:44,900
SPK_1: It's like, if you remember, there is a verse,

88
00:07:45,820 --> 00:07:49,360
SPK_1: I have said before you life and death, blessing and cursing.

89
00:07:49,420 --> 00:07:50,600
SPK_1: The Lord choose life.

90
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:53,700
SPK_1: That both of you and your descendants may live.

91
00:07:53,880 --> 00:07:58,040
SPK_1: And you can say that every crisis on a different level presents the same choice.

92
00:07:58,160 --> 00:07:58,820
SPK_1: You can choose life.

93
00:07:58,880 --> 00:07:59,540
SPK_1: You can choose death.

94
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:03,380
SPK_1: And that's why I think it's important exactly to talk about it right now.

95
00:08:04,340 --> 00:08:12,680
SPK_1: When we live in a moment where I still witness for the last, let's say, three years, focusing closely, exactly this walk-a-mole game.

96
00:08:12,820 --> 00:08:14,260
SPK_1: I think it's a very beautiful metaphor.

97
00:08:14,340 --> 00:08:19,960
SPK_1: So attempts to trying to put new wine into the old.

98
00:08:21,160 --> 00:08:22,340
SPK_1: Into the old sack.

99
00:08:22,520 --> 00:08:24,320
SPK_1: So you can use it to be comparable.

100
00:08:24,900 --> 00:08:26,620
SPK_1: But my question would be very straightforward.

101
00:08:26,940 --> 00:08:28,020
SPK_1: So what is the pillar?

102
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:31,680
SPK_1: You mentioned that like everything is shaking, platform is shaking.

103
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:33,780
SPK_1: And maybe it's the pillar which is shaking.

104
00:08:33,980 --> 00:08:35,160
SPK_1: So what do you define as a pillar?

105
00:08:35,340 --> 00:08:37,220
SPK_1: So what do you think is shaking?

106
00:08:39,380 --> 00:08:40,180
SPK_1: So there's...

107
00:08:40,180 --> 00:08:41,120
SPK_1: What was revealed to you?

108
00:08:41,220 --> 00:08:41,500
SPK_1: Sorry.

109
00:08:41,780 --> 00:08:42,220
SPK_0: Yes, yes.

110
00:08:42,260 --> 00:08:42,780
SPK_0: I love this.

111
00:08:42,780 --> 00:08:43,500
SPK_0: What is revealed.

112
00:08:45,240 --> 00:08:46,160
SPK_0: And by the way, I agree.

113
00:08:46,300 --> 00:08:47,840
SPK_0: I think all the points you added there are very good.

114
00:08:47,940 --> 00:08:48,640
SPK_0: So yes.

115
00:08:50,660 --> 00:08:51,900
SPK_0: Let me see.

116
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:54,440
SPK_0: Okay.

117
00:08:54,500 --> 00:08:59,040
SPK_0: So there's three things that are at least somewhat independent.

118
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:06,960
SPK_0: One is that as it turns out, civilizations have cycles.

119
00:09:07,060 --> 00:09:10,240
SPK_0: And there's lots of people who have written about them in different ways.

120
00:09:10,460 --> 00:09:12,860
SPK_0: But the bottom line is civilizations have cycles.

121
00:09:13,180 --> 00:09:21,080
SPK_0: And our civilization, I'm going to put that in quotes for the moment because we'll need to dig into what I am pointing to there.

122
00:09:21,080 --> 00:09:26,620
SPK_0: But our civilization is nearing the end of its natural arc.

123
00:09:26,840 --> 00:09:28,980
SPK_0: So it is sort of past senescence.

124
00:09:29,020 --> 00:09:29,760
SPK_0: I'm sorry.

125
00:09:29,820 --> 00:09:31,960
SPK_0: Past maturity and is in senescence.

126
00:09:31,980 --> 00:09:33,760
SPK_0: Or in fact, I would argue is actually undead.

127
00:09:35,860 --> 00:09:47,740
SPK_0: Second, and not directly connected but deeply related, is that oftentimes civilizations produce changes in the world,

128
00:09:48,760 --> 00:09:54,240
SPK_0: which changes are beyond the capacity of that kind of civilization to address.

129
00:09:55,160 --> 00:09:55,840
SPK_0: Okay.

130
00:09:56,780 --> 00:10:00,840
SPK_0: And so for as a simple example, I mean, there's many, many examples.

131
00:10:00,940 --> 00:10:17,720
SPK_0: But as a simple example, we might say the state of the world, world's capacity to perceive and activate peace in 1945 was not equal to the novel capacity to destroy the world in the context of modern civilization.

132
00:10:17,720 --> 00:10:30,180
SPK_0: And so that civilization, which is sort of the holdover of the Victorian British Empire, had to innovate an entirely new capacity to respond to this new possibility.

133
00:10:30,400 --> 00:10:32,440
SPK_0: There's no such possibility prior to then.

134
00:10:32,760 --> 00:10:36,640
SPK_0: So civilizations sort of went away, went their way without having to deal with it.

135
00:10:36,660 --> 00:10:39,860
SPK_0: This new possibility was something that could not have been addressed at that point.

136
00:10:40,020 --> 00:10:47,420
SPK_0: And so the category of the international order or the global order had to be produced in some fashion,

137
00:10:47,420 --> 00:10:49,740
SPK_0: which we saw, to be able to address it at all.

138
00:10:49,860 --> 00:10:52,160
SPK_0: And by the way, sort of nip and tuck, right?

139
00:10:52,200 --> 00:10:54,120
SPK_0: It wasn't obvious that it was going to make it through.

140
00:10:54,180 --> 00:10:54,700
SPK_0: It's still not obvious.

141
00:10:56,920 --> 00:10:58,280
SPK_0: And this happens all over the place.

142
00:10:58,340 --> 00:11:00,800
SPK_0: Some classic examples are, for example, just population.

143
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:03,920
SPK_0: If a civilization is very successful, the population grows.

144
00:11:04,180 --> 00:11:10,060
SPK_0: But the population's growth produces a wide variety of different consequences and very complex consequences,

145
00:11:10,700 --> 00:11:15,380
SPK_0: which at some point will outstrip the civilization's ability to continue to maintain itself.

146
00:11:15,460 --> 00:11:16,840
SPK_0: It's cybernetic.

147
00:11:17,460 --> 00:11:18,540
SPK_0: Autopoetic feedback loops.

148
00:11:20,140 --> 00:11:21,740
SPK_0: The third, which is...

149
00:11:21,740 --> 00:11:25,560
SPK_0: And now we're going to start getting into the things that are unique in our current environment.

150
00:11:25,820 --> 00:11:32,840
SPK_0: The third is this weird thing about the recursive self-building element of technology.

151
00:11:33,860 --> 00:11:39,620
SPK_0: The famous curve, the exponential curve, which in the West we call Kurzweil.

152
00:11:39,740 --> 00:11:41,580
SPK_0: I know there's a Russian who did it first and better.

153
00:11:41,680 --> 00:11:44,900
SPK_0: So I can't remember his name right now, but I think his stuff is better.

154
00:11:44,980 --> 00:11:45,300
SPK_0: But...

155
00:11:46,840 --> 00:11:49,160
SPK_0: It does seem to be something like that, that there's something about...

156
00:11:49,760 --> 00:11:52,620
SPK_0: And I think the reason is actually pretty straightforward, which is...

157
00:11:53,420 --> 00:11:56,740
SPK_0: It is very, very difficult to innovate some new idea.

158
00:11:56,900 --> 00:11:58,380
SPK_0: It's difficult to invent calculus.

159
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:00,040
SPK_0: It's difficult to invent arithmetic.

160
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:01,680
SPK_0: It's difficult to invent the laser.

161
00:12:01,840 --> 00:12:06,720
SPK_0: But once it's been invented, it's relatively easy to learn how to do it again.

162
00:12:06,980 --> 00:12:11,100
SPK_0: So it moves from the state of hard innovation into a new baseline.

163
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:14,880
SPK_0: Once it's a new baseline, new capabilities can get built on top of that.

164
00:12:14,940 --> 00:12:16,340
SPK_0: And this creates a laddering effect,

165
00:12:16,340 --> 00:12:17,920
SPK_0: which produces an exponential growth.

166
00:12:18,560 --> 00:12:23,420
SPK_0: And so while it is the case that new technologies are part of the second category,

167
00:12:23,520 --> 00:12:30,340
SPK_0: the fact that we are now caught in what seems quite clearly to be an accelerating rate of change is novel.

168
00:12:31,060 --> 00:12:39,100
SPK_0: And that acceleration is happening inside the adaptive frame that humans are able to deal with.

169
00:12:39,920 --> 00:12:40,800
SPK_0: Let me think.

170
00:12:42,160 --> 00:12:46,060
SPK_0: Yeah, let me just give you a bit of a frame here, just as an example of something that's useful.

171
00:12:46,060 --> 00:12:53,140
SPK_0: So I'm going to be dropping in some of the civilization theory that we produced over the sort of 15 year timeframe.

172
00:12:54,680 --> 00:12:58,400
SPK_0: If you're living in a world where the world that you live in,

173
00:12:58,440 --> 00:13:01,820
SPK_0: I mean this largely the physical and technical world that you live in,

174
00:13:01,860 --> 00:13:06,520
SPK_0: is effectively equivalent to the one that your great great grandfather lived in,

175
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:09,380
SPK_0: then a number of things follow.

176
00:13:09,840 --> 00:13:15,220
SPK_0: The first is you won't typically have any sense or any idea of progress.

177
00:13:15,220 --> 00:13:19,420
SPK_0: You'll typically live in a world that has a basic circular metaphysics.

178
00:13:19,860 --> 00:13:22,180
SPK_0: Seasons change, days cycle.

179
00:13:22,540 --> 00:13:23,780
SPK_0: People are born and die.

180
00:13:23,900 --> 00:13:28,300
SPK_0: But in some sense, that death is going to be reconnected to a rebirth several generations.

181
00:13:28,440 --> 00:13:29,340
SPK_0: That's something like that.

182
00:13:30,340 --> 00:13:37,620
SPK_0: And there will be no need and in fact, no capacity to imagine your culture changing.

183
00:13:37,740 --> 00:13:41,900
SPK_0: Your culture is well suited to the world that you're in for a long enough period of time

184
00:13:41,900 --> 00:13:45,200
SPK_0: that the only thing that matters is in fact that you're able to make progress.

185
00:13:45,220 --> 00:13:48,780
SPK_0: You're able to maintain it and that you're able to prevent it from changing.

186
00:13:48,940 --> 00:13:49,700
SPK_0: That's the key.

187
00:13:50,480 --> 00:13:57,640
SPK_0: But as if something happens where there is a rate of change that begins to bring it such that

188
00:13:57,640 --> 00:13:59,880
SPK_0: within that two or three generations span,

189
00:14:00,180 --> 00:14:05,340
SPK_0: your world is different enough from your great grandfather's world that it's noticeable.

190
00:14:05,500 --> 00:14:11,820
SPK_0: And there has had to have been some changes to the nature of how human beings view their world,

191
00:14:11,900 --> 00:14:13,380
SPK_0: view their role in their world,

192
00:14:13,980 --> 00:14:15,820
SPK_0: and respond to the world that they live in

193
00:14:15,820 --> 00:14:18,620
SPK_0: in order to simply respond to the real changes that have occurred.

194
00:14:19,420 --> 00:14:21,360
SPK_0: Then you're in a different kind of world.

195
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:24,180
SPK_0: First of all, there will be something like an arrow to time.

196
00:14:24,400 --> 00:14:25,280
SPK_0: Something like that.

197
00:14:25,580 --> 00:14:27,240
SPK_0: First, it'll maybe look like long circles.

198
00:14:27,320 --> 00:14:28,620
SPK_0: But at some point, it'll begin to flatten.

